WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Hello, I'm Dhruvi, a member of the Positron team, and I wanted to talk to you about the Multiple Sessions feature we added and how it's going to improve your multitasking workflows.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:22.000
So this is a feature that has been asked for a lot. We know it's been requested in RStudio for a while, and in Positron this made the top five list of most requested features.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.000
I think I'd been on the team less than a day when I found out this is what I'd be working on before I went GA in July.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And in March of 2025, we finally got to introduce this to Positron.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:42.000
You'll notice that this feature is referred to by a couple different names, Multiple Console Sessions or Multiple Interpreter Sessions. It's all the same feature in case that naming confuses you a bit.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
I'm going to be referring to it as Multiple Interpreter Sessions.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:56.000
So the first thing I want to do is walk us through how this feature works, like how you create a session, give you an overview of the session UI, and then talk about what an active session is.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:03.000
The main way you interact with Interpreter Sessions is through the console pane. You create sessions via the Create button.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.000
You've already got a session. Clicking the plus button creates a copy of the active session. That's the highlighted session.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And we'll learn a little bit more about what the active session is later.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:19.000
But if you click the dropdown next to the plus button, you'll see a list of runtimes Positron has discovered. You can pick one from there to create a session for it.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.000
So once we've got more than one session, you'll see them listed to the right of the console pane.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:31.000
These are all the sessions that are running concurrently. This means you can have each one running code at the same time.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
We've also introduced icons to the left of the session names that indicate the code execution state.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
So these icons are used to communicate whether a session is idle or if it's busy executing code.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
This should make it really easy to see the state of each session at a glance.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
You can also rename your sessions. This is handy when you need to tell sessions of the same runtime apart.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.000
So we know how to create and manage sessions. Next question is, how do we know which session the IDE is using?

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:06.000
That's where the active session comes in. The active session is the one you've selected from the console pane that is powering the IDE.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Editor helpers like Code Completions and Diagnostics use this active session.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:17.000
So when the active session changes, the editor context also instantly updates.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And it's not just editor features. Other UI panes like Plots and Variables also get updated to show you results from this active session.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So we've got the basics of managing sessions down. Now I want to walk us through a couple different use cases

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:37.000
that really highlight how multiple sessions removes a lot of friction from multitasking workflows when compared to RStudio.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
We're going to focus on having two concurrent sessions, but this does work for any number of sessions.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
I'm sure many of you have been in the situation where you have a long-running task you need to kick off

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.000
and a data set that you want to do some analysis on at the same time.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.000
In RStudio, you'd probably have handled this by starting a background job or maybe by having two separate RStudio instances open.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:03.000
In Positron, all you have to do is create another session from the console pane like we covered earlier.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
You could have two sessions of the same runtime running different code.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
The only thing you need to be aware of is which session is active when you go to execute a piece of code.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
And this is all with that native UI support in the IDE that you're used to.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.000
You also get to keep the full state of logs, variables, execution history, and errors for each session.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
When it comes to using different runtime versions of a language,

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
we know in RStudio getting multiple IDE instances up against different R versions involves setting an environment variable,

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:38.000
setting a directory alias, or even using a third-party tool.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
But because Positron was made with the intention to natively run against different runtimes,

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.000
the ability to run concurrent sessions isn't limited to a single runtime version.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:52.000
So if you're trying to test your code against two versions of R, like R4.3 and R4.6,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
you can get both versions running at the same time.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.000
And comparing outputs across both is really simple because the context of each session is just a single click away.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
So this can be helpful if you're a package developer, instructor,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
or anyone who needs to maintain backwards and forwards compatibility for a project.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
I want to wrap up with this last idea, which is that you're not limited to your sessions being in the same language either.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Positron's a polyglot IDE, which means you can have sessions for different languages running side by side.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.000
So if there's a Python package that makes data cleaning a breeze, but you want to use R and Shiny for everything else,

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
you can create a workflow to do that pretty easily in Positron.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
So whether it's different runtimes or even different languages,

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
multitasking should be easier with a lot less friction now.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Thank you.

